        }
      ],
      "text": "<p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">Which of the following modifications is primarily responsible for the inactivation of genes found within CpG islands?</span></p>",
      "unique_key": "Q4447727",
      "question_audio": null,
      "question_video": null,
      "map_id": 30389,
      "difficulty_level": "intermediate",
      "subjects_id": [
        1
      ],
      "solution": "<p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Ans. A. Methylation</strong></span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Option A:</strong></span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Methylation,</strong> specifically the addition of a <strong>methyl group to the cytosine nucleotides</strong> within <strong>CpG islands</strong>, is a well-known <strong>epigenetic mechanism</strong> that <strong>leads to the inactivation of genes.</strong> This <strong>modification</strong> can alter the <strong>accessibility of the DNA to transcriptional machinery</strong>, effectively <strong>silencing gene expression</strong>. Methylation of CpG islands in gene promoter regions is a key regulatory mechanism in gene expression, playing significant roles in various biological processes and diseases.</span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong><u>Explanation:</u></strong></span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Option</strong></span><span style=\"font-size:11pt;\"> </span><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>B. Phosphorylation:</strong> While phosphorylation is a <strong>crucial post-translational modification </strong>that <strong>affects protein function</strong>, it is not directly involved in the inactivation of genes within CpG islands.</span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Option</strong></span><span style=\"font-size:11pt;\"> </span><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>C. Ubiquitination:</strong> Ubiquitination is a <strong>process that tags proteins </strong>for <strong>degradation </strong>and does not directly affect gene inactivation at the DNA level within CpG islands.</span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Option</strong></span><span style=\"font-size:11pt;\"> </span><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>B. Acetylation:</strong> Acetylation, particularly of <strong>histone proteins</strong>, is generally associated with the <strong>activation of gene expression </strong>by making chromatin more accessible to transcriptional machinery, not inactivation.</span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong><u>Educational Objective:</u></strong></span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Gene promoters and regulation by methylation and demethylation:</strong></span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><ul><li><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Majority of gene promoters </strong>have <strong>high CG content</strong>.</span></p></li><li><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">CpG islands are the most common sites of methylation-demethylation.</span></p></li><li><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">Thus, they play an important role in regulation of gene expression</span></p></li><li><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">CpG islands of promoters are typically unmethylated, which favours transcription.</span></p></li></ul><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong><u>Ref</u>: DM Vasudevan 9/e: p 596</strong></span></p>",
