          "text": "<p><span style=\"font-size:12pt;\">DNA methylation</span></p>"
        }
      ],
      "text": "<p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt;\">A neonate presents with marked hypotonia, necessitating tube feeding, and displays distinct facial characteristics, including almond-shaped eyes and downturned mouth corners, suggestive of a genetic disorder. Given the clinical presentation and the suspicion of Prader-Willi syndrome, the physician orders chromosomal analysis and DNA testing to investigate a specific chromosome 15 abnormality and potential genomic imprinting issues. Which molecular process, occurring at the 5th position of cytidine and often associated with gene silencing, is most relevant to the testing ordered for this patient?</span></p>",
      "unique_key": "Q9646800",
      "question_audio": null,
      "question_video": null,
      "map_id": 30387,
      "difficulty_level": "intermediate",
      "subjects_id": [
        1
      ],
      "solution": "<p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt;\"><strong>Ans. D) DNA methylation</strong></span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt;\"><strong>Option D:</strong></span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><ul><li><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt;\"><strong>DNA methylation</strong> occurs mainly at <strong>CpG dinucleotides</strong> that often <strong>cluster in the upstream promoter regions of genes</strong> (CpG islands).</span></p></li><li><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt;\"><strong>Chromosomes</strong> subject to <strong>genomic imprinting</strong> might have <strong>different DNA methylation</strong> patterns on the <strong>homologue transmitted</strong> from <strong>mother versus that transmitted by father,</strong> producing <strong>balanced expression</strong> which is disrupted in disorders such as <strong>Prader-Willi syndrome.</strong></span></p></li></ul><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt;\"><strong><u>Explanation:</u></strong></span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt;\"><strong>Option A:</strong> <strong>Gene conversion</strong> involves the <strong>process where one DNA sequence</strong> is <strong>converted to another,</strong> which is not directly related to the epigenetic silencing observed in Prader-Willi syndrome.</span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt;\"><strong>Option B:</strong> <strong>Sister chromatid exchange</strong> is a <strong>mechanism where identical sister chromatids exchange genetic material </strong>during <strong>cell division,</strong> not typically associated with gene silencing or the pathology of Prader-Willi syndrome.</span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt;\"><strong>Option C:</strong> <strong>Gene rearrangement</strong> refers to the <strong>reorganization of genetic material </strong>within the <strong>genome, </strong>which can play a role in certain diseases but is not the primary mechanism behind Prader-Willi syndrome, which involves specific epigenetic modifications like DNA methylation.</span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt;\"><strong><u>Educational Objective:</u></strong></span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt;\"><strong>DNA methylation,</strong> particularly at the <strong>5th carbon position </strong>of <strong>cytosine bases</strong> (5-methylcytosine), is a key <strong>epigenetic modification</strong> that can lead to <strong>gene silencing.</strong> In the context of <strong>Prader-Willi syndrome,</strong> this modification is relevant because the <strong>disorder</strong> is often associated with the <strong>loss of paternally inherited genes on chromosome 15</strong> due to <strong>deletions or alterations in genomic imprinting,</strong> where DNA methylation plays a crucial role.</span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt;\"><strong><u>Ref</u>: DM Vasudevan 9/e: p 582.</strong></span></p>",
