        {
          "id": 37419,
          "text": "<p><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Acetylation </span></span></span></p>"
        },
        {
          "id": 37420,
          "text": "<p><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Methylation</span></span></span></p>"
        },
        {
          "id": 37421,
          "text": "<p><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Sumoylation</span></span></span></p>"
        },
        {
          "id": 37422,
          "text": "<p><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Phosphorylation </span></span></span></p>"
        }
      ],
      "text": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">A group of geneticists is reviewing epigenetic modifications to determine which ones are typically associated with a permissive state of chromatin, allowing gene transcription. They aim to identify which modification is not generally associated with a more open chromatin configuration conducive to transcription. Which of the following chromatin modifications is usually not considered permissive for gene expression?</span></span></span></p>",
      "unique_key": "Q2760612",
      "question_audio": null,
      "question_video": null,
      "map_id": 30391,
      "difficulty_level": "difficult",
      "subjects_id": [
        1
      ],
      "solution": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Ans. B) Methylation</span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option B:</span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><strong>Methylation</strong>, especially of <strong>cytosine bases </strong>in the <strong>DNA </strong>and certain <strong>lysine residues </strong>on <strong>histone proteins </strong>(such as methylation of histone H3 on lysine 9, H3K9), is commonly associated with <strong>chromatin compaction </strong>and <strong>transcriptional repression</strong>. This <strong>modification leads</strong> to a <strong>more condensed chromatin state</strong>, known as <strong>heterochromatin</strong>, which is generally <strong>not permissive for gene transcription.</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Explanation:</span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option A: </span></strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><strong>Acetylation</strong> and </span><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option D</span></strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">: <strong>Phosphorylation</strong> of <strong>histone adds negative charge</strong>. This <strong>-ve charge repels negative charge </strong>of <strong>DNA.</strong> So, <strong>DNA </strong>become <strong>free from histones </strong>and <strong>available for transcription</strong>. Acetylation &amp; Phosphorylation of Histones leads to Euchromatin formation or permissive chromatin formation.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option D:</span></strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"> <strong>Sumoylation </strong>is the <strong>attachment of small ubiquitin-like modifier </strong>(SUMO) <strong>proteins </strong>to <strong>target proteins</strong>, including <strong>histones</strong>. <strong>Sumoylation </strong>of <strong>histones </strong>can have <strong>variable effects </strong>on <strong>gene expression</strong>, but it is generally associated with gene repression by promoting the formation of repressive chromatin structures. However, the role of sumoylation is not yet very clearly defined. </span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">So, the one best answer is methylation which has clear well defined role on gene inactivation. But for multiple answers, both Methylation and Sumoylation can be marked.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Educational Objective:</span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><strong>Methylation</strong> is often associated with <strong>chromatin compaction</strong> and <strong>transcriptional repression</strong>, while <strong>acetylation </strong>and <strong>phosphorylation</strong> generally <strong>promote a more open chromatin structure</strong> and <strong>active transcription</strong>, is crucial for <strong>grasping the complexities of gene regulation mechanisms</strong> at the <strong>epigenetic level.</strong> Sumoylation&#39;s role is more variable and context-dependent, illustrating the nuanced nature of epigenetic regulation.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"PT-BR\" style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Ref</span></u></strong><strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"PT-BR\" style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">: DM Vasudevan 9 e p: 604.</span></strong> <span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">(Ref: </span><a href=\"https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/%20pmc/articles/PMC8216275/\" style=\"color:blue; text-decoration:underline\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/ pmc/articles/PMC8216275/</span></a><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">)</span></span></span></p>",
