        }
      ],
      "text": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Which of the following options correctly describes Epigenetics?</span></span></span></p>",
      "unique_key": "Q1681292",
      "question_audio": null,
      "question_video": null,
      "map_id": 30388,
      "difficulty_level": "intermediate",
      "subjects_id": [
        1
      ],
      "solution": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Ans. A. Chemical modification of DNA</span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Option A:</span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><strong>Epigenetics </strong>involves the <strong>study of heritable changes </strong>in <strong>gene function </strong>that <strong>do not involve changes </strong>in the <strong>DNA sequence</strong>. These <strong>changes </strong>can be achieved through various mechanisms, one of the most common being the <strong>chemical modification of DNA</strong>, such as <strong>DNA methylation</strong>. Epigenetic modifications can also include modifications to histone proteins and changes in chromatin structure, affecting gene expression without altering the underlying DNA sequence.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Explanation: </span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Option</span></strong> <strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">B. Irreversible modification of DNA: </span></strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Epigenetic modifications are <strong>typically reversible</strong>, allowing for dynamic changes in gene expression in response to environmental stimuli or developmental cues.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Option</span></strong> <strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">C. Change in nucleotide sequence:</span></strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"> Epigenetics does <strong>not involve changes to the DNA sequence </strong>itself; it involves modifications that affect how genes are expressed.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Option</span></strong> <strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">D. Normal variation of nucleotides:</span></strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"> This option might describe <strong>genetic polymorphisms </strong>or variations that occur naturally within populations, not epigenetic changes.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Educational Objective:</span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Mechanisms of Genomic Imprinting</span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">DNA methylation</span></span></span></strong></li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<ul style=\"margin-left:40px\">\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">most common mechanism</span></span></span></li>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">occurs at CG site/CG Island/CpG sites (C &amp; G together present on same strands)</span></span></span></li>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">cytosine is usually methylated in CG site that causes inactivation of the gene</span></span></span></li>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">DNA methylation can be detected by Na bisulfite method.</span></span></span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<ol start=\"2\">\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">PTM of Histones: </span></span></span></strong>\r\n\r\n\t<ul style=\"list-style-type:disc\">\r\n\t\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Histone Deacetylation</span></span></span></li>\r\n\t\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Histone Methylation</span></span></span></li>\r\n\t\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Methods to detect PTMs: Chromatin Immuno Precipitation (ChIP)</span></span></span></li>\r\n\t</ul>\r\n\t</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Ref</span></u></strong><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">: Harper 30/e page 440.</span></strong></span></span></p>",
