        }
      ],
      "text": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">which of the presented processes correctly relates to the changes in gene expression regulation depicted in the image?</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://cerebellum-web-static.s3.amazonaws.com/media/public/images/2024/04/06/picture1_cZQT8Ie.jpg\" style=\"height:190px; width:300px\" /></span></span></span></p>",
      "unique_key": "Q6272701",
      "question_audio": null,
      "question_video": null,
      "map_id": 30392,
      "difficulty_level": "difficult",
      "subjects_id": [
        1
      ],
      "solution": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Ans. C. Alter organization of the DNA </span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Option C:</span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">This <strong>regulatory mechanism </strong>is <strong>&lsquo;epigenetic modification&rsquo; </strong>which does <strong>not affect </strong>or <strong>alter the nucleotide sequence</strong>.<strong> </strong></span></span></span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">The <strong>chemical modification of DNA </strong>or <strong>chromatin activates </strong>or <strong>inhibits gene expression. </strong></span></span></span></li>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><strong>Increased euchromatin formation activates </strong>the <strong>gene and heterochromatin formation </strong>causes <strong>inactivation of the gene</strong>. Thus, it affects the organisation of DNA.</span></span></span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Explanation: </span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Option A. Post transcriptional regulation:</span></strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"> It is an <strong>epigenetic modification.</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Option B. Affect mRNA stability</span></strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"> affects the <strong>organisation of DNA </strong>but has no effect on mRNA stability.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Option D. Alter the nucleotide sequence of the DNA: </span></strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">epigenetic modification does <strong>not affect </strong>or alter the <strong>nucleotide sequences</strong>.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Educational Objective</span></u></strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">: </span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><strong>DNA methylation </strong>and <strong>histone acetylation</strong>, both of which are <strong>epigenetic modifications</strong>. These <strong>modifications </strong>are known to <strong>affect the structure </strong>and <strong>organization of DNA </strong>in the <strong>chromatin</strong>, influencing <strong>gene expression </strong>by regulating the accessibility of transcriptional machinery to certain genes.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Ref</span></u></strong><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">: Harper 30/e: p 371-376, Lippincott 7/e: P 409-410.</span></strong></span></span></p>",
