      ],
      "text": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Acetylation and deacetylation of lysine residues on histone proteins results in a mechanism by which transcription can be activated or repressed. Which one of the following histone proteins least likely participates in this process?</span></span></span></p>",
      "unique_key": "Q5937031",
      "question_audio": null,
      "question_video": null,
      "map_id": 30390,
      "difficulty_level": "intermediate",
      "subjects_id": [
        1
      ],
      "solution": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Ans. A) H1</span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option A:</span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><strong>Nucleosomes </strong>are <strong>disk shaped particles </strong>which consist of a <strong>core of histone protein </strong>around which <strong>DNA is wrapped </strong>(short linker region of DNA joins nucleosomes). </span></span></span></li>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">The <strong>core of the nucleosomes</strong>: <strong>Two copies</strong> each of <strong>histones H2A, H2B, H3, and H4</strong>. </span></span></span></li>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">These <strong>histone proteins</strong> have <strong><em>N</em>-terminal &ldquo;tails&rdquo; </strong>which contain <strong>lysine residues </strong>that can be <strong>reversibly acetylated</strong>, thereby <strong>affecting the electrostatic </strong>interaction of the <strong>DNA </strong>with <strong>these histones</strong>. </span></span></span></li>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><strong>Histone H1 </strong>is <strong>not </strong>a <strong>part of the nucleosomes core</strong>, therefore acetylation will not affect the protein&ndash;DNA interaction of the nucleosomes.</span></span></span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><br />\r\n<span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><u>Explanation:</u></span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option B, Option C, Option D</span></strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">. <strong>Histones H2A</strong>, <strong>H2B</strong>, <strong>H3</strong>, and <strong>H4 </strong>make up the <strong>core of the nucleosome</strong>, and their <strong>N-terminal tails </strong>are subject to various <strong>post-translational modifications</strong>, including <strong>acetylation </strong>and <strong>deacetylation</strong>, which play direct roles in the regulation of transcription.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Educational Objective:</span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><strong>Histone H1 </strong>is known as the <strong>linker histone</strong>, and while it plays a <strong>role in the structure of chromatin</strong>, it is <strong>less directly </strong>involved in the <strong>modification processes</strong>, such as <strong>acetylation </strong>and <strong>deacetylation</strong>, that <strong>regulate transcription</strong>.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Ref</span></u></strong><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">: Harper 30/e:&nbsp; p 371-375.</span></strong></span></span></p>",
